[1
Date: 28 Dec 2001
From: Richard Montali <montalir@nzp.si.edu>


Here are a few more "reverse zoonoses" (aka zooanthroponoses) to add to the
list. Diseases that have been strongly suspected, or documented as having
been transmitted from humans to animals include _Mycobacterium
tuberculosis_ (from humans to nonhuman primates, Asian elephants and
psitticine birds), hepatitis A ( from humans to New World monkey species),
and herpesvirus simplex (from humans to marmosets and tamarins).

Montali RJ. Important aspects of zoonotic diseases in zoo and wildlife
species. Verh ber Erkrg Zootiere 1999; 39: 149-55.
Montali RJ, Mikota SK, Cheng LI. Mycobacterium tuberculosis in zoo and
wildlife species. Scientific and Technical Review, International Office of
Epizootics 2001; 20(1): 291-303.

--
Richard Montali
<montalir@nzp.si.edu>

