[2
Date: Fri, 28 Dec 2001 09:43:26 -0200
From: "Fernando DA Pires" <favila@matrix.com.br>


I have been puzzeled by the expression "reverse zoonosis" in [recent
issues of ProMED-mail. The term "zoonosis" was originally used by German
authors for "diseases of animals". It was later applied, in a loose
fashion, to "diseases of animals transmitted to man".

In 1959 a Joint Committee of Experts on Zoonosis from WHO and FAO defined
zoonoses as "diseases naturally transmitted among man and other
vertebrates"(see Fiennes R. Zoonoses and the origins and ecology of human
diseases. London: Acad Press, 1978).

Epidemiologists and parasitologists often use expressions like
"anthroponosis", "anthropozoonosis", and
"zooanthroponosis" inconsistently. Russian and some eastern European
authors use "zooanthroponosis" for what WHO/FAO defined as "zoonosis" (see
Galuzo IG. Twenty years of natural-nidality studies. In: Levine ND
(editor). Natural nidality of diseases and questions of parasitology.
Urbana: Univ. Illinois Press, 1968).

Furthermore, current definitions of these terms are not ethimologically
correct. Such expressions are reminiscent of an anthropocentrism which is
alien to sound biological, evolutionary, and ecological thought. And it
would be almost impossible to demonstrate, in many instances, if a disease
affects more human beings or more non-human vertebrates.

--
Prof Dr Fernando Dias de Avila Pires
Instituto Oswaldo Cruz/UFSC
